"""
mkt-original | Leviticus | chapters 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-leviticus-19-21-fill.py

Ch 19: The Holiness Code core — "be holy as I am holy"; ethicized holiness
        (neighbor-love, gleaning for poor, just weights); ch 19 v18 already present.
Ch 20: Capital punishment schedule — Molech, cursing parents, sexual violations,
        mediums; the death-penalty framework that calibrates Holiness Code severity.
Ch 21: Priestly holiness — corpse-defilement restrictions, marriage regulations,
        disqualifying physical defects; graded strictness: priests < high priest.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses — the revelation formula opens the Holiness Code's ethical summit, ch 19, which gathers the widest range of social, ritual, and agricultural legislation under a single theological principle.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>Qedoshim tihyu ki qadosh ani YHWH Eloheichem</em> — be holy (<em>qedoshim</em>) for I, YHWH your God, am holy. This is the foundational axiom of Lev 17–26: holiness is not primarily ritual separation but participation in the divine character. The plural <em>qedoshim</em> addresses the entire congregation (<em>edah</em>) of Israel, not only the priests; holiness is a communal, not merely sacerdotal, vocation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Each of you shall revere (<em>tira'u</em>) his mother and his father, and you shall keep my Sabbaths — the two primary relational loyalties (family and divine rhythm) are placed at the head of the chapter's legislation. The reversal of the Decalogue's order (mother before father, Exod 20:12: father first) is deliberate, noting the mother's authority deserves explicit acknowledgment.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Do not turn to idols (<em>elilim</em>) and do not make for yourselves cast gods — <em>elilim</em> is a wordplay on <em>el</em> (God/strength): idols are non-gods, nothings. The plural command echoes the Decalogue's first two commandments (Exod 20:3-4), which the chapter's structure deliberately recapitulates.</p>",
    "5": "<p>When you offer a peace offering (<em>zevach shelamim</em>) to YHWH, you shall offer it so that you may be accepted — the peace offering legislation (vv.5-8) enforces the time limit from Lev 7:15-18: the fellowship offering must be eaten within two days; eating on the third day renders it an abomination (<em>pigul</em>).</p>",
    "6": "<p>It shall be eaten on the day you offer it or on the day after, and anything left over until the third day shall be burned up with fire — the two-day window (day of offering + next day) applies to the <em>toda</em> (thanksgiving) variant (Lev 7:15) and the <em>neder/nadavah</em> (vow/freewill) variant (Lev 7:16); burning the remainder prevents fermentation and ritual contamination.</p>",
    "7": "<p>If it is eaten at all on the third day, it is tainted (<em>pigul</em>); it will not be accepted — <em>pigul</em> (foul, abomination of ritual impurity) is a technical term for an offering rendered void by improper timing or wrong intention; it cannot generate atonement for the offerer even if consumed.</p>",
    "8": "<p>And everyone who eats it shall bear his iniquity (<em>avono yissa</em>), because he has profaned what is holy to YHWH, and that person shall be cut off (<em>venikhreta</em>) from his people — eating <em>pigul</em> activates the <em>karet</em> penalty, which applies to high-handed violations of sacred boundaries throughout Leviticus. The eating of a ritually void sacrifice extends its defilement to the eater.</p>",
    "9": "<p>When you harvest the harvest of your land, you shall not reap your field right up to its edge (<em>pe'ah sadekha</em>), nor shall you gather the gleanings after your harvest — the pe'ah (corner/edge) law requires leaving unharvested strips at field edges; the leket (gleaning) law prohibits picking up stalks that fall during reaping. Both provisions create a legal agricultural safety net for the poor and sojourner.</p>",
    "10": "<p>And you shall not strip your vineyard bare (<em>lo te'olel</em>), neither shall you gather the fallen grapes of your vineyard. You shall leave them for the poor and for the sojourner — the vineyard parallel to the field law (v.9): <em>olel</em> (small clusters missed in harvest) and <em>peret</em> (individual fallen grapes) must be left. Ruth 2 exemplifies the gleaning system working as intended: Boaz's field follows these laws.</p>",
    "11": "<p>You shall not steal (<em>lo tignovu</em>). You shall not deal falsely (<em>lo techachedu</em>). You shall not lie (<em>lo teshakru</em>) to one another — three verbs form a progression from action (theft) to relational act (dealing falsely) to speech (lying). The placement after the gleaning laws and before the oath laws connects economic, relational, and verbal integrity as a single ethical domain.</p>",
    "12": "<p>You shall not swear by my name falsely (<em>lo tishave'u bishmi lashaqer</em>), and so profane the name of your God — invoking YHWH's name in a false oath treats the divine name as a guarantee for a lie, profaning (<em>cillel</em>) the Name's character. This is the Decalogue's third commandment (Exod 20:7: do not take the name of YHWH in vain) restated in oath-context form.</p>",
    "13": "<p>You shall not oppress your neighbor (<em>lo ta'ashoq</em>) or rob him. The wages of a hired worker shall not remain with you all night until the morning — withholding wages overnight exploits the day-laborer who depends on daily payment for daily food (cf. Deut 24:14-15; Jas 5:4). The prohibition on <em>oshek</em> (oppression) and <em>gazal</em> (robbery) frames wage theft as economic violence against neighbors.</p>",
    "14": "<p>You shall not curse the deaf (<em>lo teqallel cheresh</em>) or put a stumbling block before the blind (<em>ve-lifney iver lo titten mikhshol</em>), but you shall fear your God — exploiting vulnerability that the victim cannot perceive (the deaf cannot hear the curse; the blind cannot see the obstacle) is precisely what <em>fear of God</em> prohibits. The two examples represent all forms of taking advantage of those who cannot self-defend.</p>",
    "15": "<p>You shall do no injustice (<em>lo ta'asu avel</em>) in judgment. You shall not be partial to the poor (<em>lo tissa feney-dal</em>) or defer to the great (<em>lo tehdar feney gadol</em>), but in righteousness shall you judge your neighbor — judicial impartiality is required in both directions: not showing pity to the poor (which distorts justice) and not deferring to the powerful (which sells justice). <em>Tzedek</em> (righteousness) requires consistent standard regardless of social status.</p>",
    "16": "<p>You shall not go around as a slanderer (<em>lo telech rachil</em>) among your people, and you shall not stand up against the life (<em>dam</em>) of your neighbor — <em>rachil</em> (slanderer/gossip, literally 'trader/peddler') suggests someone who traffics in others' reputations. The second clause (<em>lo ta'amod al-dam re'ekha</em>, do not stand against your neighbor's blood) prohibits either false accusation that could result in execution or failure to act when a neighbor's life is in danger.</p>",
    "17": "<p>You shall not hate your brother in your heart (<em>lo-tisna et-achikha bilvavekha</em>). You shall reason frankly with your neighbor (<em>hokheach tokhiach et-amitekha</em>), lest you incur sin because of him — the internal dimension of community ethics: the heart-hatred that never erupts in overt conflict but festers. The antidote is direct, honest rebuke (<em>tokhach</em>) rather than suppressed resentment — a theme central to both Matt 18:15-17 and rabbinic ethics (Avot 2:10).</p>",
    "19": "<p>You shall keep my statutes (<em>chuqqotai tishmoru</em>). You shall not let your cattle breed with a different kind (<em>kil'ayim</em>). You shall not sow your field with two kinds of seed (<em>sha'atnez</em>), nor shall you wear a garment of cloth made of two kinds of material — the <em>kil'ayim</em> (two-kinds, hybrid) prohibitions: animal crossbreeding, mixed-seed planting, and mixed-fiber weaving. These laws enforce created categories (Gen 1: each after its kind), treating the blurring of boundaries as a violation of creation order rather than a mere ritual taboo.</p>",
    "20": "<p>If a man lies sexually with a woman who is a slave, assigned to another man but not yet ransomed or given her freedom, a distinction shall be made — the slave-concubine case: she is betrothed or designated but not yet legally free. The case is treated as a crime requiring <em>biqqoret</em> (inquiry/investigation), with a guilt offering but not death, because her slave status means she does not have the full legal capacity to be held to the capital standard of Lev 20:10.</p>",
    "21": "<p>He shall bring his guilt offering (<em>asham</em>) to YHWH, to the entrance of the tent of meeting — the <em>asham</em> is the reparation offering for violations involving sacred property or rights (Lev 5:14-6:7). The man has violated the woman's assigned betrothal-right; the guilt offering covers this reparable violation.</p>",
    "22": "<p>And the priest shall make atonement for him with the ram of the guilt offering before YHWH for his sin that he has committed, and he shall be forgiven for the sin that he has committed — the standard atonement-forgiveness formula; despite the severity of the violation (sexual exploitation of a protected woman), atonement is available through the <em>asham</em>, unlike the cases in Lev 20 that carry the death penalty.</p>",
    "23": "<p>When you come into the land and plant any kind of tree for food, you shall regard its fruit as forbidden (<em>areltem orlato</em>). Three years it shall be forbidden to you; it must not be eaten — <em>orlah</em> (foreskin/uncircumcision) is the term for the fruit of years 1–3; treating it as uncircumcised (forbidden, consecrated away) allows the tree to establish root structure without premature harvesting. The agricultural wisdom is embedded in purity language.</p>",
    "24": "<p>And in the fourth year all its fruit shall be holy (<em>qodesh hillulim</em>), an offering of praise to YHWH — the fourth year's fruit is entirely consecrated to YHWH, brought to Jerusalem (cf. Deut 14:23) as first-fruit acknowledgment. <em>Hillulim</em> (praise, celebration) links the fourth-year offering to rejoicing rather than mere obligation.</p>",
    "25": "<p>But in the fifth year you may eat of its fruit, to increase its yield for you — the five-year cycle (1-3 forbidden, 4th consecrated, 5th for eating) creates a development sequence: YHWH receives first; then the farmer benefits. The promise <em>lehosif lachem tevuato</em> (to increase its yield for you) grounds the delayed gratification in covenantal blessing.</p>",
    "26": "<p>You shall not eat any flesh with the blood in it (<em>al ha-dam</em>). You shall not interpret omens (<em>lo tenacheshu</em>) or tell fortunes (<em>lo te'onenu</em>) — blood-eating prohibition (cf. Lev 17:10-14; Deut 12:16) precedes the divination prohibitions; both treat illegitimate access to life-force (blood) and forbidden knowledge (omens) as violations of divine sovereignty over life.</p>",
    "27": "<p>You shall not round off the hair on your temples (<em>lo taqifu pe'at roshechem</em>) or mar the edges of your beard (<em>ve-lo tashchit et pe'at zeqanekha</em>) — mourning rites involving specific beard/hair cutting are prohibited (cf. Lev 21:5; Deut 14:1); these were associated with pagan mortuary practices. The prohibition preserves Israelite distinctiveness from Canaanite grief rites.</p>",
    "28": "<p>You shall not make any cuts on your body for the dead (<em>seret la-nefesh</em>) or tattoo yourselves (<em>uktovat qa'aqa lo titenu bachem</em>); I am YHWH — gashing the body for the dead (cf. 1 Kgs 18:28 for the prophets of Baal) and permanent body marking both associated with pagan mourning/devotion practices. The divine self-identification formula (<em>ani YHWH</em>) terminates the clause, grounding the prohibition in covenant identity.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Do not profane your daughter by making her a prostitute (<em>lo techallel et-bitkha lehaznotah</em>), lest the land fall into prostitution and the land become full of depravity (<em>zimah</em>) — sacred or cultic prostitution (common in Canaanite fertility religion) would have been the proximate reference; but the prohibition extends to any exploitation of one's daughter for sexual gain. The connection to the land becoming full of <em>zimah</em> links sexual ethics to territorial holiness (cf. Lev 18:24-28).</p>",
    "30": "<p>You shall keep my Sabbaths (<em>et-shabtotai tishmoru</em>) and reverence my sanctuary (<em>miqdashi tira'u</em>); I am YHWH — Sabbath observance and sanctuary reverence form a paired refrain (cf. Lev 26:2) that frames the ethical legislation of the Holiness Code; time (Sabbath) and space (sanctuary) are the two axes of holy order around which all ethical life is organized.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Do not turn to mediums (<em>ha-ovot</em>) or necromancers (<em>ha-yidde'onim</em>); do not seek them out to be defiled by them — <em>ov</em> (medium/spirit of the dead) and <em>yidde'oni</em> (familiar spirit/wizard) are the two terms used in Lev 20:27 (capital offense) and 1 Sam 28:7-8 (Saul's consultation at En-dor). Consulting the dead usurps YHWH's monopoly on revelation and knowledge.</p>",
    "32": "<p>You shall stand up before the gray head (<em>mipenei seva taqum</em>) and honor the face of an old man (<em>ve-hadarta peney zaqen</em>), and you shall fear your God — respect for the elderly is grounded in fear of God, not merely social convention; the same divine self-identification formula (<em>ani YHWH</em>) that grounds the prohibition on idolatry also grounds respect for the aged. The community's attitude toward its most vulnerable members reflects its theological character.</p>",
    "33": "<p>When a stranger (<em>ger</em>) sojourns with you in your land, you shall not do him wrong (<em>lo tonu oto</em>) — the <em>ger</em> (resident alien, sojourner) lacks clan protection; the prohibition on oppression (<em>yanh</em>) is the first of a paired command, with the positive counterpart in v.34. Israel's own sojourn in Egypt is the experiential ground for sojourner ethics throughout the Torah.</p>",
    "34": "<p>You shall treat the stranger who sojourns with you as the native among you, and you shall love him as yourself (<em>ve-ahavta lo kamocha</em>), for you were strangers in the land of Egypt — the sojourner-love command uses the identical formulation as the neighbor-love command of v.18 (<em>ve-ahavta le-re'akha kamocha</em>). The application of the universal principle to the specific case of the outsider expands the covenant community's ethical radius.</p>",
    "35": "<p>You shall do no wrong (<em>lo ta'asu avel</em>) in judgment, in measures of length or weight or quantity — the just-weights legislation (vv.35-36) applies the anti-injustice principle of v.15 (judicial integrity) to commercial transactions; <em>avel</em> (injustice) covers both legal and commercial fraud, treating dishonest scales as a form of perversion of justice.</p>",
    "36": "<p>You shall have just balances (<em>mozney tzedeq</em>), just weights (<em>avney tzedeq</em>), a just ephah (<em>eifah tzedek</em>), and a just hin (<em>hin tzedeq</em>); I am YHWH your God who brought you out of the land of Egypt — four instruments of honest commerce (balance, stone weight, dry measure, liquid measure) named explicitly; the exodus formula grounds commercial ethics in the same redemptive identity that grounds every other covenantal obligation. Dishonest trade is not merely illegal but a repudiation of the redeemer God.</p>",
    "37": "<p>And you shall observe all my statutes (<em>kol-chuqqotai</em>) and all my rules (<em>kol-mishpatai</em>) and do them; I am YHWH — the Holiness Code chapter closes with a summary command to keep all the statutes and rules, followed by the foundational self-identification. The pairing <em>chuqqim</em> (statutes, non-transparent commands) and <em>mishpatim</em> (judgments, rationally transparent civil laws) encompasses the full range of Levitical legislation.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses — ch 20 provides the capital punishment schedule for violations enumerated in chs 18 and 19. The sequence ch 18 (prohibition) → ch 20 (penalty) is interrupted by ch 19's broad ethical code, which contextualizes the sexual prohibitions within the larger pattern of holiness ethics.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Say to the people of Israel: Any one of the people of Israel or of the strangers who sojourn in Israel who gives any of his children to Molech shall surely be put to death (<em>mot yumat</em>). The people of the land shall stone him with stones — Molech sacrifice (child-burning, cf. Lev 18:21; 2 Kgs 23:10; Jer 32:35) is the first and most severe prohibition; the double infinitive absolute <em>mot yumat</em> (dying he shall die) signals irreversible capital punishment. The community execution by stoning makes the entire people the instrument of judgment.</p>",
    "3": "<p>I myself will set my face against that man and will cut him off from among his people, because he has given one of his children to Molech, to make my sanctuary unclean (<em>lema'an tamme et-miqdashi</em>) and to profane my holy name — the double offense of Molech sacrifice: it defiles the sanctuary (the impurity of child-murder touches even YHWH's holy space) and profanes the Name (Israel's child-sacrifice is a desecration of covenant identity). Even if the community fails to execute the offender (v.4), divine <em>karet</em> applies.</p>",
    "4": "<p>And if the people of the land do at all close their eyes to that man when he gives one of his children to Molech, and do not put him to death — communal negligence (looking the other way at Molech sacrifice) creates communal guilt. The following verse (v.5) extends divine judgment to the negligent community, treating silence in the face of atrocity as complicity.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Then I will set my face against that man and against his clan and will cut them off from among their people, him and all who follow him in whoring after Molech — the clan (<em>mishpachto</em>) shares in the guilt of the individual Molech worshiper; collective culpability extends to all who follow the same path (<em>ha-zonim acharav</em>, those who whore after Molech). The language of spiritual adultery (<em>znut</em>) frames idolatry as covenant infidelity.</p>",
    "6": "<p>If a person turns to mediums (<em>ha-ovot</em>) and necromancers (<em>yidde'onim</em>), whoring after them, I will set my face against that person and will cut him off — consulting the dead is spiritual adultery (<em>znut</em>) just as Molech worship is; both divert loyalty due to YHWH toward illegitimate supernatural powers. The divine self-initiated karet (v.6) operates even when the community does not formally prosecute.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Consecrate yourselves (<em>hitqaddashtem</em>), therefore, and be holy (<em>vihyitem qedoshim</em>), for I am YHWH your God — the positive command embedded within the penalty schedule; holiness is not merely avoiding the prohibited behaviors but actively orienting oneself toward YHWH. The reflexive <em>hitqaddashtem</em> (consecrate yourselves) implies ongoing, personal, intentional separation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Keep my statutes (<em>shemartem et-chuqqotai</em>) and do them; I am YHWH who sanctifies you (<em>ani YHWH meqaddishchem</em>) — the declaration that YHWH is the one who sanctifies Israel (<em>meqaddish</em>) is the ground, not the result, of Israel's holiness; Israel is called to embody a holiness that YHWH first effects. The same formula appears in Lev 21:8,15,23; 22:9,16,32.</p>",
    "9": "<p>For anyone who curses his father or his mother shall surely be put to death (<em>mot yumat</em>); he has cursed his father or his mother; his blood is upon him (<em>damo bo</em>) — the capital offense of cursing parents (Exod 21:17; Prov 20:20) is placed immediately after the holiness call, connecting family order to the covenant structure. The phrase <em>damo bo</em> (his blood is on him) absolves the executioners of blood-guilt; the condemned bears the consequence of his own act.</p>",
    "10": "<p>If a man commits adultery (<em>nif'al na'aph</em>) with the wife of his neighbor, both the adulterer and the adulteress shall surely be put to death — adultery (Exod 20:14) is capital for both parties; the equal punishment of man and woman is significant in an ancient Near Eastern context where adultery laws often focused exclusively on the woman. Both <em>ha-na'ef</em> (the adulterer) and <em>ha-no'evet</em> (the adulteress) are subject to <em>mot yumat</em>.</p>",
    "11": "<p>If a man lies with his father's wife, he has uncovered his father's nakedness (<em>ervat aviv gilla</em>); both of them shall surely be put to death; their blood is upon them — intercourse with a father's wife (stepmother, not biological mother) is incest under the Levitical framework. The language <em>ervat aviv gilla</em> (he has uncovered his father's nakedness) implies violation of the father's domain and honor, not only the woman's personhood.</p>",
    "12": "<p>If a man lies with his daughter-in-law (<em>kalato</em>), both of them shall surely be put to death; they have committed perversion (<em>tevel asu</em>); their blood is upon them — <em>tevel</em> (confusion, perversion) is the term used for violation of species/status boundaries; daughter-in-law intercourse violates the family structure that marriage creates. Both parties receive capital punishment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>If a man lies with a male as with a woman (<em>mishkevey isha</em>), both of them have committed an abomination (<em>to'evah asu</em>); they shall surely be put to death; their blood is upon them — <em>to'evah</em> (abomination) is the term applied in Lev 18:22; the penalty schedule confirms capital punishment for both parties. The two-term sequence <em>tevel</em> (perverted confusion of order) and <em>to'evah</em> (abomination) covers both natural-order violation and divine-disgust violation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>If a man takes a woman and her mother also, it is depravity (<em>zimah hi</em>); he and they shall be burned with fire, that there may be no depravity among you — taking a woman and her mother (Lev 18:17) is <em>zimah</em> (wickedness, lewdness); burning is the most severe execution mode in Leviticus, used here and for the high priest's daughter who prostitutes herself (Lev 21:9). The collective judgment (all three burned) reflects that all three participated in the violation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>If a man lies with an animal, he shall surely be put to death (<em>mot yumat</em>), and you shall kill the animal — bestiality (Lev 18:23; Exod 22:19; Deut 27:21) is capital for the man and requires the killing of the animal; the animal's execution prevents ongoing association with the violation and removes an instrument that caused the defilement.</p>",
    "16": "<p>If a woman approaches any animal and lies with it, you shall kill the woman and the animal; they shall surely be put to death; their blood is upon them — the female parallel: a woman who approaches an animal for sexual contact is equally subject to capital punishment. The symmetrical treatment of male and female bestiality is consistent with the ch 20 pattern of equal penalties for both parties.</p>",
    "17": "<p>If a man takes his sister, a daughter of his father or a daughter of his mother, and sees her nakedness and she sees his nakedness, it is a disgrace (<em>chesed hu</em>); they shall be cut off (<em>venikhrevu</em>) in the sight of the children of their people — sibling incest (Lev 18:9) receives <em>karet</em> rather than immediate capital execution; the term <em>chesed</em> here is an archaic use meaning 'disgrace/reproach' rather than the more common covenant-love meaning. Public <em>karet</em> (in the sight of the people) is social as well as divine exclusion.</p>",
    "18": "<p>If a man lies with a woman during her menstrual period (<em>niddah</em>) and uncovers her nakedness, he has made naked her fountain (<em>et-mekorah ereh</em>), and she has uncovered the fountain of her blood. Both of them shall be cut off from among their people — the niddah violation (Lev 18:19; 15:24) carries <em>karet</em> (not immediate capital punishment) for both parties. The Hebrew <em>mekorah</em> (source, fountain) uses bodily imagery for the generative source; <em>ereh</em> is the same root as <em>ervah</em> (nakedness, the term used throughout chs 18 and 20).</p>",
    "19": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your mother's sister or of your father's sister, for that is to make naked one's relative (<em>et-she'ero ereh</em>); they shall bear their iniquity — aunt-nephew relationships (Lev 18:12-13) do not carry capital punishment here but the bearing of iniquity (<em>avon yissau</em>), implying a lesser but still significant degree of guilt. <em>She'er</em> (flesh-relation, close kin) is the basis of the prohibition.</p>",
    "20": "<p>If a man lies with his uncle's wife, he has uncovered his uncle's nakedness (<em>dodato gilla</em>); they shall bear their sin (<em>chet'am yissau</em>); they shall die childless (<em>ariyrim yamuthu</em>) — uncle's wife violation (Lev 18:14) results in dying childless (<em>ariri</em>) rather than execution; the punishment is the absence of covenant continuation — no posterity. Childlessness in the Israelite context was understood as a covenantal consequence, not merely biological misfortune.</p>",
    "21": "<p>If a man takes his brother's wife, it is impurity (<em>niddah hi</em>); he has uncovered his brother's nakedness (<em>achiv gilla</em>); they shall be childless — brother's wife violation (Lev 18:16; cf. Deut 25:5-10 where levirate marriage is the exception that proves the rule) results in childlessness. The tension between the Lev 20:21 prohibition and the Deut 25 levirate provision is resolved by noting the Deut 25 exception applies only when the brother died without an heir.</p>",
    "22": "<p>You shall therefore keep all my statutes and all my rules and do them, that the land where I am bringing you to live may not vomit you out (<em>vataqe ha-aretz etchem</em>) — the land-vomiting image from Lev 18:25-28 recurs; the land itself responds to moral defilement by expelling its inhabitants. Covenant obedience is not merely personal ethics but the condition for continued habitation in the promised land.</p>",
    "23": "<p>And you shall not walk in the customs of the nation that I am driving out before you, for they did all these things, and therefore I detested them — Canaanite practices (all the sexual and religious violations listed in chs 18 and 20) are the reason for Canaanite expulsion; Israel is warned not to replicate the pattern that brought divine judgment on the prior inhabitants. The conquest is simultaneously punishment of Canaan and warning to Israel.</p>",
    "24": "<p>But I have said to you, 'You shall inherit their land, and I will give it to you to possess, a land flowing with milk and honey.' I am YHWH your God, who has separated you from the peoples (<em>hifdal eschem min-ha'ammim</em>) — the divine promise of possession (<em>yerushah</em>) frames the holiness requirement: separation from the nations' practices is the precondition for inheriting the nations' land. YHWH's separation of Israel from the peoples corresponds to Israel's separation of clean from unclean (v.25).</p>",
    "25": "<p>You shall therefore separate (<em>hivdaltem</em>) the clean beast from the unclean, and the unclean bird from the clean. You shall not make yourselves detestable by beast or by bird or by anything with which the ground crawls — the kashrut taxonomy of Lev 11 is recalled here as the dietary dimension of the same separateness principle governing sexual ethics; Israel's dietary, sexual, and social separateness form a unified holiness stance toward the surrounding nations.</p>",
    "26": "<p>You shall be holy to me, for I YHWH am holy and have separated you from the peoples, that you should be mine (<em>lihyot li</em>) — the climactic statement of the Holiness Code's social and sexual legislation: holiness is YHWH's own character, communicated to Israel through the separation-act of election. The purpose of holiness (<em>lihyot li</em>, to be mine) frames all ethical requirements as expressions of covenantal belonging rather than mere legal compliance.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A man or a woman who is a medium (<em>ov</em>) or a necromancer (<em>yidde'oni</em>) shall surely be put to death. They shall be stoned with stones; their blood shall be upon them — the capital penalty for mediums and necromancers (cf. v.6 for the client; here the practitioner) closes the chapter. Stoning is the standard communal execution; the blood-guilt formula absolves the community. Saul's violation of this law at En-dor (1 Sam 28:7-19) represents the same pattern of covenant infidelity that led to his rejection.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>And YHWH said to Moses, 'Speak to the priests, the sons of Aaron, and say to them' — the double address (YHWH to Moses → Moses to the priests) signals that the priestly legislation of ch 21 is mediated through Moses to Aaron's sons specifically; the priests are the subject of ch 21's regulations, not the entire people as in chs 19–20.</p>",
    "2": "<p>No one shall make himself unclean for the dead among his people, except for his nearest kin (<em>le-she'ero ha-qarov elav</em>): his mother, his father, his son, his daughter, his brother — the priest's general restriction from corpse-defilement has explicit exceptions for the seven closest relatives (vv.2-3); corpse impurity (Num 19) lasts seven days and disqualifies from sanctuary service. The priest's vocation requires limiting the normal human obligation to mourn the dead physically.</p>",
    "3": "<p>His virgin sister (<em>achoto ha-vetulah ha-qerovah elav</em>) who is near to him because she has had no husband; for her he may make himself unclean — the unmarried sister who has no husband to mourn her is included in the permissible exceptions; she remains under her brother's protection until marriage, and he retains the mourning obligation for her as for other nearest kin.</p>",
    "4": "<p>He shall not make himself unclean as a husband among his people and so profane himself — the Hebrew is difficult; <em>ba'al be'ammav</em> may mean 'as a leading man among his people' (i.e., he must not defile himself in ways inappropriate to his rank) or may refer to defilement for a wife's relatives beyond the immediate household. The priestly status creates a stricter standard than ordinary Israelites face.</p>",
    "5": "<p>They shall not make bald patches on their heads (<em>lo yiqrechu qorchah be-roshecha</em>), nor shave off the edges of their beards (<em>pe'at zeqanam lo yegalleihu</em>), nor make any cuts on their bodies — the same mourning-rite prohibitions of Lev 19:27-28 are repeated specifically for priests; what is forbidden to all Israelites (Lev 19:27) is especially forbidden to priests whose bodies serve in the sanctuary. The prohibitions align with 21:4: the priest's body must be maintained for sanctuary service.</p>",
    "6": "<p>They shall be holy to their God and not profane the name of their God (<em>lo yechalelu shem Eloheihem</em>), for they offer the LORD's food offerings (<em>ishei YHWH</em>), the bread of their God (<em>lechem Eloheihem</em>); therefore they shall be holy — the ground of priestly holiness: they handle the food of God. The expression <em>lechem Eloheihem</em> (bread of their God) uses the language of the divine table (Lev 3:11,16; Num 28:2) to explain why the priest's body and life must be consecrated above the ordinary Israelite level.</p>",
    "7": "<p>They shall not marry a prostitute or a woman who has been defiled (<em>zonah vechalala lo yiqqachu</em>), neither shall they marry a woman divorced from her husband, for the priest is holy to his God — the priest's marriage partner must share the holiness standard; a <em>zonah</em> (prostitute) or <em>chalala</em> (profaned woman, one born of a prohibited priestly union) or divorcee would introduce defilement into the priestly household. The prohibition is not judgment on the woman's person but recognition that the priestly household must maintain a higher purity standard.</p>",
    "8": "<p>You shall sanctify him therefore, for he offers the bread of your God. He shall be holy to you, for I, YHWH, who sanctify you, am holy (<em>qadosh ani YHWH meqadishchem</em>) — the congregation is addressed: they bear responsibility for maintaining the priest's holiness standards. The formula <em>qadosh ani YHWH meqadishchem</em> (I am YHWH who sanctifies you) grounds the priestly holiness requirement in the divine character, not merely in cultic regulation.</p>",
    "9": "<p>And the daughter of any priest, if she profanes herself by whoring (<em>ki tachel liznot</em>), she profanes her father; she shall be burned with fire — the priest's daughter who prostitutes herself receives the most severe execution (burning, cf. Lev 20:14) because her conduct profanes her father's sacred office. The priest's household represents an extension of his sacred character; its defilement defiles his priestly capacity.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The priest who is chief among his brothers (<em>ha-kohen ha-gadol me-echav</em>), on whose head the anointing oil has been poured and who has been consecrated to wear the garments, shall not let the hair of his head hang loose (<em>lo yifra rosho</em>) or tear his clothes — the high priest has stricter mourning restrictions than ordinary priests; he may not display any of the standard mourning gestures (loose hair, torn garments, cf. Lev 10:6) even for the death of nearest kin.</p>",
    "11": "<p>He shall not go in to any dead bodies nor make himself unclean, even for his father or for his mother — the high priest's prohibition extends even to parents; no exception is made as it is for ordinary priests (vv.2-3). The high priest's complete separation from corpse impurity reflects his unique role as the one who enters the most holy place; his continual cultic purity cannot be interrupted even for family bereavement.</p>",
    "12": "<p>He shall not go out of the sanctuary lest he profane the sanctuary of his God (<em>ve-et-miqdash Elohav lo yechalel</em>), for the consecration of the anointing oil of his God is upon him; I am YHWH — the high priest is confined to the sanctuary area even during mourning periods; his departure would profane the sanctuary by associating it with the corpse-defilement he would contract. The anointing oil that consecrates him creates an inseparable bond with the sanctuary that constrains his movements.</p>",
    "13": "<p>And he shall take a wife in her virginity (<em>bevtuloteha yiqqach ishah</em>) — the high priest must marry a virgin; his marriage partner requirement is the strictest of all (ordinary priests may not marry prostitutes or divorcees, v.7; high priests must specifically marry virgins). The requirement ensures the high priest's household is free of prior sexual history that could compromise ritual purity.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A widow, or a divorced woman, or a woman who has been defiled, or a prostitute, these he shall not marry. But he shall take as his wife a virgin from his own people (<em>min-amav</em>) — the four prohibited marriage partners for the high priest: widow (<em>almanah</em>), divorcee (<em>gerushah</em>), defiled woman (<em>chalala</em>), prostitute (<em>zonah</em>). The positive requirement adds <em>min-amav</em> (from his own people), which rabbinic tradition interprets as requiring an Israelite woman, not a proselyte.</p>",
    "15": "<p>That he may not profane his offspring among his people, for I am YHWH who sanctifies him — the purpose of the marriage restriction: to preserve the holiness of the high priestly lineage. <em>Zar'o</em> (his seed/offspring) must not be mixed with women whose status would compromise the priestly succession. The divine self-identification formula again grounds the requirement in YHWH's own sanctifying character.</p>",
    "16": "<p>And YHWH spoke to Moses, saying — a new revelation formula introduces the legislation on disqualifying physical conditions (vv.17-23), separating it as a distinct legal unit from the marriage and mourning regulations of vv.1-15.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Speak to Aaron, saying: None of your offspring throughout their generations who has a blemish (<em>mum</em>) may approach to offer the bread of his God — the legislation on physical disqualification is addressed to Aaron specifically (not to Aaron's sons as in v.1), because it concerns his lineage's priestly capacity. <em>Mum</em> (blemish, defect) is the same term used for sacrificial animals (Lev 1:3; 3:1; 22:20); the parallel between unblemished animal and unblemished priest is structural and deliberate.</p>",
    "18": "<p>For no one who has a blemish shall draw near: a man blind or lame (<em>iver o pisseach</em>), or one who has a mutilated face or a limb too long (<em>charumm o sarua</em>) — the first four disqualifying conditions: blindness, lameness, mutilated nose (or flat nose), disproportionate limb. These are physical conditions that would make the priest visually conspicuous at the altar; the rationale is aesthetic-representational, not moral.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Or a man who has an injured foot or an injured hand (<em>shever regel o shever yad</em>) — broken foot or hand (whether healed with deformity or actively broken); the term <em>shever</em> (fracture) suggests structural damage rather than temporary injury. These conditions would impair the physical actions of priestly service at the altar.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Or a hunchback or a dwarf (<em>gibben o daqq</em>), or a man with a defect in his sight (<em>tevalul be-eyno</em>) or an itching disease (<em>garav</em>) or scabs (<em>yalefet</em>) or crushed testicles (<em>meroach ashekh</em>) — six additional conditions extending the list: spinal deformity, stunted growth, eye disorder (cataract/spot), chronic skin conditions, and genital damage. The comprehensive list covers conditions visible, structural, dermal, and reproductive.</p>",
    "21": "<p>No man of the offspring of Aaron the priest who has a blemish shall come near to offer the LORD's food offerings; since he has a blemish, he shall not come near to offer the bread of his God — the summary prohibition: the blemish disqualifies from approach (<em>yiqqrav</em>) to the altar and from offering (<em>lehaqriv</em>) the food-offerings. The disability does not excommunicate the priest from the community or from his priestly identity, only from active altar ministry.</p>",
    "22": "<p>He may eat the bread of his God, both of the most holy and of the holy things (<em>miqqodesh ha-qedashim umin-ha-qedashim yokhal</em>) — the physically disqualified priest retains full access to priestly food portions: both the most-holy offerings (Lev 2:3,10; 6:17,25,29; 7:1,6) and the lesser-holy offerings. His altar service is suspended but his priestly identity and its material privileges remain fully intact.</p>",
    "23": "<p>But he shall not go through the veil (<em>el-ha-parochet lo yavo</em>) or approach the altar, because he has a blemish, that he may not profane my sanctuaries (<em>mikdashay lo yechalel</em>), for I am YHWH who sanctifies them — the two forbidden zones: the veil (access to the inner sanctuary/most holy place) and the altar. The priest with a blemish would profane these spaces not through moral failure but through structural incongruity with the symbolism of wholeness the sanctuary requires. The <em>meqadishchem</em> formula closes the section with the same divine sanctifying authority that grounds all priestly requirements.</p>",
    "24": "<p>So Moses spoke to Aaron and to his sons and to all the people of Israel — Moses addresses all three audiences: Aaron (head of the priestly order), his sons (the priests in service), and all Israel (who must honor the disqualification provisions). The broad audience confirms that the physical qualification system is public knowledge, not an internal priestly secret.</p>"
  }
}

